    "Mitchell G. Reddish, Nijay K. Gupta": "David `[char_David_Rut_4]` Garland makes this point about 1 Cor 9:27: \u201cDiscipline for discipline\u2019s\nsake . . . does not drive him. He buffets his body and makes it his slave to heighten his\ncapacity to deny himself to serve others\u201d; see 1 Corinthians (BECNT; Grand Rapids MI:\nBaker, 2003) 443.",
    "Ruckman, Dr. Peter S_": "Our Lord is speaking of His coming death on the cross. \u201cThe cup,\u201d here, turns out to be \u201cmy cup,\u201d not the Father\u2019s cup [v_Jhn_18_11] (John `[char_John_Ref]` 18:11). The personal pronouns here are very important. The FATHER\u2019S CUP, about which Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` prays in the Garden of [v_Mat_26_42] Gethsemane (Matt. 26:42), is never spoken of anywhere as representing PHYSICAL death\u2014check the passages in Jeremiah [v_Isa_51_17] 25:15; Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 51:17;\nPsalm 75:8, 60:3. \u201cChrist\u2019s CUP,\u201d spoken of [v_Mat_20_23] here (Matt. 20:23), can be identified with physical death in\nverse",
    "Unknown": "A song of victory like that of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` after crossing the Red Sea. And the song of the Lamb `[animal_Lamb_Jhn_1]` ( t\u00ean \u00f4id\u00ean tou arniou ). A separate note of victory like that of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`, though one song, not two. Charles finds it impossible to reconcile the two expressions, if genuine, but it is a needless objection. The words come from the O.T.: &quot;great&quot; ( megala ) from Ps 111:2, &quot;wonderful&quot; ( thaumasta ) from Ps 139:14, &quot;O Lord God the Almighty&quot; ( Kurie ho theos ho pantokrat\u00f4r ) from Amos 4:13 (Rev 4:8), &quot;righteous and true&quot; ( dikaiai kai al\u00eathinai ) from Deut 32:4, &quot;Thou King of the ages&quot; ( ho basileus t\u00f4n ai\u00f4n\u00f4n ) like Jer 10:10; 1Ti 1:\n19. For naos see Rev 3:12; Rev 7:15; Rev 14:15, 17; Rev 16:1,\n19. A song of victory like that of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` after crossing the Red Sea. And the song of the Lamb (t\u00ean \u00f4id\u00ean tou arniou). A separate note of victory like that of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`, though one song, not two. Charles finds it impossible to reconcile the two expressions, if genuine, but it is a needless objection. The words come from the O.T.: \"great\" (megala) [v_Psa_111_2] from Ps 111:2, \"wonderful\" (thaumasta) from Ps 139:14, \"O Lord [v_Amo_4_13] God the Almighty\" (Kurie ho theos ho pantokrat\u00f4r) from Amos 4:13 [v_Rev_4_8] (Rev 4:8), \"righteous and true\" (dikaiai kai al\u00eathinai) from Deut 32:4, \"Thou King of the ages\" (ho basileus t\u00f4n ai\u00f4n\u00f4n) like Jer 10:10; 1Ti 1:\n19. For naos see Rev 3:12; Rev 7:15; Rev 14:15, 17; Rev 16:1,\n19. Only here the figure of bride is not the [v_Rev_19_7] people of God as in Rev 19:7, but the abode of the people of God (the New Jerusalem). For her husband (t\u00f4i andri aut\u00eas). Dative case of personal interest.\n19. Did lighten it (eph\u00f4tisen aut\u00ean). First aorist active indicative of ph\u00f4tiz\u00f4, to [v_Luk_11_36] illumine, old verb from ph\u00f4s (Luke 11:36). If the sun and moon did shine, they would give no added light in the presence of the [v_Rev_21_11] Shekinah Glory of God. See verse Rev 21:11 for \"the glory of God.\" [v_Rev_18_1] Cf. Rev 18:1; Rev 21:3. \"Their splendour is simply put to shame by the glory of God Himself\" (Charles). And the lamp thereof is the Lamb (kai ho luchnos aut\u00eas to arnion). Charles takes ho luchnos as predicate, \"and the Lamb is the lamp thereof.\" Bousset thinks that John `[char_John_Ref]` means to compare Christ to the moon the lesser light (Gen 1:16), but that contrast is not necessary. Swete sees Christ as the one lamp for all in contrast with the many luchniai of the churches on [v_Rev_1_12] earth (Rev 1:12, 20). \"No words could more clearly demonstrate the purely spiritual character of St. John `[char_John_Ref]`'s conception of the New Jerusalem\" (Swete).",
