    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "In the harvest there is discrimination in judgement. Hasadiah. [Hasadi'ah] Son of Zerubbabel, a descendant of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. 1 Chr. 3:\n20. Hasenuah. [Hasenu'ah] Father of Hodaviah of the tribe of Benjamin. 1 Chr. 9:\n20. Abba [Ab'ba] The Greek form is \u1f00 \u03b2\u03b2 \u1fb6 father: it is the same as Ab in Hebrew, but was pronounced Abba in the time of our Saviour. It occurs three times in the New Testament, and is always followed by 'father,' and translated Abba Father; that is, the 'abba' is transcribed and not translated: if it were translated it would be 'Father Father.' In the Greek it stands thus: \u1f00 \u03b2\u03b2 \u1fb6 \u1f41 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c4 \u1f75 \u03c1 the 'Abba' being Aramaic, and the 'Father' Greek. In the, Old Testament Ab was not restricted in its use to children. Elisha used it toward Elijah; servants applied it to their masters, etc.: see 2 Kings 2: 12 ; 2 Kings 5: 13; 2 Kings 6: 21, etc. Jehovah asked, &quot;Hath the rain a father?&quot; Job 38:\n20. Joash was hid in a bed-chamber, or a room adapted to that purpose, apparently connected with the temple. 2 Kings 11:",
