    "Unknown": "The number seven seems particularly appropriate here for finality and completeness.\n7. John `[char_John_Ref]` thus combines in Hebraic tone the expressions of the old and the new in the song to the Glorified Messiah.\n7. Arrayed ( endedumenoi ). Perfect passive participle of endu\u00f4 . With precious stone pure and bright ( lithon katharon lampron ). Accusative case retained with verb of clothing as so often, literally &quot;with a stone pure bright.&quot; For both adjectives together see Rev 19:8,\nVerse 7\n7. The number seven seems particularly appropriate here for finality and completeness.\n7. John `[char_John_Ref]` thus combines in Hebraic tone the expressions of the old and the new in the song to the Glorified Messiah.\n7. Arrayed (endedumenoi). Perfect passive participle of endu\u00f4. With precious stone pure and bright (lithon katharon lampron). Accusative case retained with verb of clothing as so often, literally \"with a stone pure bright.\" For both adjectives together see [v_Rev_19_8] Rev 19:8,\n7. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Wife of the Lamb made herself ready in her bridal attire. As a bride adorned (h\u00f4s numph\u00ean kekosm\u00eamen\u00ean). Perfect passive participle of kosme\u00f4, old verb (from kosmos ornament like our [v_Rev_21_19] cosmetics), as in Rev 21:\n7. Verse 10 He carried me away in the Spirit (ap\u00eanegken me en pneumati). [v_Rev_17_7] See same language in Rev 17:7 when John `[char_John_Ref]` received a vision of the Harlot City in a wilderness. Here it is \"to a mountain great and high\" [v_Ezk_40_2] (epi oros mega kai hups\u00ealon). So it was with Ezekiel (Ezek 40:2) [v_Mat_4_8] and so the devil took Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (Mat 4:8). It was apparently not Mount [v_Rev_14_1] Zion (Rev 14:1), for the New Jerusalem is seen from this mountain. [v_Rev_1_10] \"The Seer is carried thither 'in spirit' (cf. Rev 1:10; Rev 4:1); the Angel's deuro is a sursum cor to which his spirit under the influence [v_Eph_1_17] of the 'Spirit of revelation' (Eph 1:17) at once responds\" (Swete). And he shewed me (kai edeixen moi). First aorist active indicative [v_Rev_21_9] of deiknumi, just as he had said he would do in verse Rev 21:9 (deix\u00f4 soi, I will shew thee). Precisely the same words about [v_Rev_21_2] Jerusalem as in verse Rev 21:2, save the absence of kain\u00ean (New).",
    "Alfred Edersheim": "And I will see my desire on him and his house. And Israel [said], I will destroy with an everlasting destruction. Now Omri took (had taken) the land\nver. 7, seems to me designedly chosen to bring out the work of Jehu as the sentence of the higher Master. ftp9 Mark the omission of the words, \u201c over the people of Jehovah,\u201d in\nver. 7, seems to me designedly chosen to bring out the work of Jehu as the sentence of the higher Master. ftp9 Mark the omission of the words, \u201c over the people of Jehovah,\u201d in",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "Numbers 28:26 [c_Num_28] [v_Num_28_26] \u201330 tells of the Feast of Weeks, also called Pentecost. What happened at a Pentecost celebration in the New Testament? What difference does this make for us?\n7. Why did the two and a half tribes decide to settle outside of the Promised Land (32:1\u201342)? Why weren\u2019t these very good reasons?\n7. What do we learn about ourselves from Israel\u2019s experience as recorded in the book of Numbers? Give an example of something you have learned about yourself during this study.\n7. The word translated \u201cburden\u201d in Galatians 6:5 [c_Gal_6] [v_Gal_6_5]  means \u201ca soldier\u2019s pack,\u201d and every soldier has to carry his own pack. If my car breaks down, my neighbor can help me by driving my children to school, but my neighbor can\u2019t assume my parental responsibilities in the home so that I can do as I please. There are some burdens that you have to shoulder and can\u2019t hand to others. C HAPTER 2",
    "William MacDonald": "is explained in\nv. 7) was fulfilled when two of Sennacherib's own sons murdered him and a third, Esarhaddon, reigned in his place. Hezekiah's Tunnel was dug through solid rock from the Pool of Siloam to Jerusalem in order to insure a supply of water for the city in case of an Assyrian attack.",
